In Czechia, we have "consume due", which is a red line limit, after which the food is not safe to consume and "best before", which means that it is perfectly safe to eat the food even after the date, as long as there are no signs of spoilage. "Consume due" is for food that spoils quickly and can become dangerous after that, while "best before" is typically used for dried or canned food. There are specialized stores, where you can buy outdated "best before" food for dirt cheap prices and use it normally. It is not so tasty, but it is a life-saver for many low-income families.

And expiration dates on non-refrigerated drugs are even MORE bogus. In the case of medicines, more often than not those expiration dates on them have nothing to do with the actual medicine, but rather they are for the PACKAGING of the medicine. Those vitamins that expired three years ago are still perfectly safe and viable to consume, but the vacuum seal on their bottle probably kicked it a while ago. The albuterol sulfate in a rescue inhaler will still work long past it's expiration date, but the canister might not have been able to hold on to the needed pressure past that date.

So if you find yourself dying for some ibuprofen and all you have is that bottle your mom sent with you to college a decade ago, don't pass it up automatically. Just spend an extra moment ensuring that a packaging breakdown hasn't contaminated the contents, and you're good to go.

Expiration dates are a failsafe to keep from getting sued. While food may last much longer than the given expiration date, the date is there so that if you try to sue them for it going bad they can say "Well the label says you should have eaten it already."

That's why most "expiration dates" are labeled as "best by." It's the time span in which the manufacturer believes it will taste the best, simple. You're really not blowing my mind. Anyone who believes food cannot be eaten after the "best by" date should see this as their own personal problem and not try to blame the manufacturers. Many are also labeled as "sell by", this is a suggestion to "middle men" (grocery stores) as to when they should sell the product as to ensure maximum consumer happiness and incentivize them to purchase the product again. Anybody who blames corporations for the fault of themselves should perhaps be a bit more introspective. And if I throw away my yogurt half-way through because I'm not very hungry does not cause a starving African to die. It's a poor financial decision on my part, and my own personal bank account is punished for it, it harms no one else. ...godlings, Adam, "nationally mandated" is the only way to do it "right?" You're really not doing anybody any favors with that kind of propaganda. If you have national mandates on food labeling, how long do you think it will be before your Hulko company will be ensuring their cronies are on the regulatory boards, mandating the dating to be exactly what Hulko thinks is optimal for THEM? It will ensure that those who actually do a better job of making longer-lasting foods (or foods that taste better longer) get labeled with Hulko's preferred dates. And, if the rhetoric you're using to push for these nationally mandated dates is echoed loudly enough, they'll justify insisting that their competitors' products that are actually not as tasty if not turned over faster ALSO must be dated at Hulko's preferred date.

What you're doing - informing consumers of what the dates actually mean - is half of the solution already. We don't need mandated anything. What we do need is educated consumers who know how to check for spoilage. 

Furthermore, throwing out all that food? Not a "crisis" of any sort. Well, except for the fact that the very people who back things like national mandates and federally-commanded welfare demagogue it if food past it's "best by" dates is donated. If anything, it means food is very cheap and affordable, since those "millions of Americans" aren't all the wicked, evil 1% that are always villified as hoarding resources. The only reason there ARE hunger problems in the world has nothing to do with Capitalist countries wasting food, and everything to do with non-Capitalist countries being led by people who will steal the food donated to their people, as well as anything their people make, and not allow their people to have enough.

Resource scarcity is really a poor resource distribution system. Capitalism is the best resource-distribution system known to man. Where it's in effect, resources are distributed so efficiently that we CAN waste them, because the effort to hoard and shepherd them costs more than the waste. If we distributed Capitalism more evenly around the world, there wouldn't be nation-wide hunger epidemics. There would still be poor people, and still be starving people, but they would be far fewer and farther between world-wide.

"BEST BEFORE" does mean that until then the food product is at its best in terms of taste, appearance, aroma, and texture. It does not mean one day past the product turned bad.  

With our modern evaluation and analysis methods manufacturers do know very well how long their product can really last, under the storage conditions mentioned on the package. Because companies will want us to have a good experience with the food item, they often will include a little room for consumer error. Some time after the date mentioned the product will usually still be perfectly eatable, but usually the flavour, aroma or appearance starts suffering.

Most companies will not give a too short Best Before, for example with the purpose to make you throw the item away early. If they do, it could be a silly move, as it could easily work against them. Consumers usually will chose the food product with the longer Best Before.

Pasteurized does not mean sterilized. They are different terms. Sterilized means completely free of life, including viruses (avoiding, for now, the debate over whether viruses are "life" or not). Pasteurized means that the microbial load has been lowered enough to increase shelf life, and kill potential pathogens, but that doesn't mean there aren't any microorganisms in the milk. In fact, that's how milk "goes bad" in the first place, via lactic acid bacteria normally found in dairy, that create, you guessed it, lactic acid, that sours the milk. In some countries (all of Europe, in particular) they use a slightly different pasteurization process, and sterilized containers so that milk can be stored on a shelf for months, without needing refrigeration until it's opened.

Not exactly true.  Pasteurization just kills bacteria present at the time of bottling.  Bacteria can still contaminate milk after it's been opened, but refrigeration slows their ability to reproduce and metabolize properly.  Given enough time (especially at room temperature), lactobacilli and different fungi can populate a milk jug and speed up the reaction of spoiling to the point that the emulsion becomes acidic enough to eat through the milk container.  Normally, they're at low enough concentrations that they can't hurt you, but the expiration date is effectively the point where the food company can no longer guarantee the quality or safety of their food products when refrigerated properly.  And the molds or lactobacilli can still make you very, very sick.  And this can happen even when the jug is refrigerated, if you give it enough time after the expiration date.  At some point, enough methane and CO2 builds up in the container, trapping more of the heat inside of the jug, speeding up the metabolism of the bacteria and fungal contaminants inside.  The emulsion again can become acidic enough to eat through plastic or paper containers, allowing these contaminants to spread to other items in the fridge.  So, it can make you sick, and pasteurization can only protect you for as long as the container hasn't been opened and been kept outside of optimum refrigeration temperatures.  A couple days or maybe even a week outside the expiration date probably won't hurt you with regards to milk, but two or three weeks just might, especially if it's spent any time sitting out.

The rest of the bacteria are reduced by 10 log which is significant however, there are still enzymes that are heat resistant which can slowly cause milk to go bad. The FDA requires that milk contains less than a certain amount of microbes up to the expiration date. It is safe to drink milk a couple of days after the expiration date but if it smells spoiled and taste spoiled it's probably spoiled.

Animal milk has long been claimed as the go-to source of calcium by the dairy industry, but as it turns out, milk is bad for you. Calcium from animal milk is not absorbed as well as that from plant-based sources, and it can be accompanied by a number of dangerous health problems.
1. Broken bones
In a Swedish medical study, women who consumed large quantities of dairy milk daily were more likely to sustain fractures than those who drank little to no milk. 
2. Prostate cancer
Some evidence suggests that the consumption of milk and other dairy products leads to an increased risk of prostate cancer. Conversely, dairy-free diets have been followed to slow the progress of prostate cancer.
3. Lactose intolerance
Cow‚Äôs milk contains a sugar called lactose that can be difficult for people to digest, resulting in symptoms such as nausea, cramps, gas, bloating, and diarrhea. It can also develop later in life and result in months of worsening symptoms.
4. Acne
In multiple studies, the consumption of all types of cow‚Äôs milk was linked to an increased prevalence and severity of acne in both boys and girls.
5. Cholesterol
A single serving of milk can contain as much as 24 mg of cholesterol, whereas vegan food has no cholesterol.
6. Ovarian cancer
A Swedish study showed that women who consumed four or more servings of dairy products each day were twice as likely to develop serous ovarian cancer as those who consumed two or fewer servings of dairy products each day.
7. Milk allergies
Unlike lactose intolerance, milk allergies, usually in young children, are characterized by potentially strong and dangerous reactions, such as vomiting or anaphylaxis.
8. Antibiotics
Many cows are pumped full of antibiotics. This practice is leading to antibiotic-resistant bacteria, which may decrease the effectiveness of antibiotics used on humans.
9. Saturated fat
A single serving of whole milk can contain more than 20 percent of the recommended daily allowance (RDA) of saturated fat, but even 1 percent milk has 8 percent of the RDA. If you consume three servings of whole milk, you‚Äôre already at 60 percent for the day, even before eating any food.
10. Weight gain
Despite industry claims, a study of more than 12,000 children showed that the more milk they drank, the more weight they gained, and skim and 1 percent milk appeared, counter-intuitively, to lead to more weight gain than drinking 2 percent or whole milk. The study also found that replacing soda with milk did not lead to weight loss.
11. Bone loss
Instead of promoting bone health, animal protein in dairy products can have a calcium-leaching effect.

These health factors, combined with the environmentally damaging nature of large-scale milk production, make it clear that milk is bad for you.

If something is past the expiration date, I just use a three-step process.
1. Look: Is there mold or any other weird changes in appearance?
2. If it looks fine, smell: does it smell rotten or otherwise not how it should?
3. If it doesn't look different or smell odd, taste: Does it taste how it's supposed to?
If it looks, tastes, and smells fine, it IS fine: I've made fondue using chocolate that was four years past its expiration date. It tasted fine and nobody who ate it got sick.

can i ask, do you think every person gets to decide for themselves, what they think is wrong and whats right?

I don't just think they get to, I know that that's the very nature of morality. There is no objectively true moral code, as there are no ethical laws of nature. Every ethical framework is premised upon inherently subjective value judgements. "Fairness is good", "malice is bad", "freedom is good", etc. These are not objectively true statements, they're value judgements that only exist within the minds of subjects. 

So basically, yes. Just as we create our own meaning and purpose in* life because there is no objective meaning and purpose to it, we create our own morality because there is no objective morality.

To ask a question of my own, do you think there is some moral code written into the fabric of reality? Is there some authority that dictates what moral codes are "true" and which are "false"? And if you think so, then what makes that authority's judgement of what is moral objective? The universe is indifferent, the only thing capable of making moral judgements is a mind. A subject. Be it something like you and I, or something great that sits upon some pedestal of authority, dictating down to the bugs what it thinks is moral.

It is an interesting question. I dont believe in god or that there is a higher authority, that wrote a moral code into the fabric of realise. But I also dont think that, for example, raping children should be seen as "well, wrong and right are just the ideas we are humans made, and everyone gets to decide and do what they think is right so we cant possibly judge this". I go by a very simple rule, I can do whatever it is I do, just as long as I dont intentionally hurt others. I dont think that because we dont have someone watching over us or telling us the rules, that there shouldnt be any. I think we, as society, need to come to together and look at things, such as, domestic abuse causes people deep trauma and upset, lets try not to do that. And, oh, affordable education and making sure everyone has something to eat makes this society as a whole better, maybe thats something we should do. Just because we dont have someone higher saying "btw child molestation isnt great for the kids", doesnt mean we cant use the tools we have, such as research, to show that it is causing society to be ill, so to say. You know what I mean? I respect your opinion and you seem like someone I would like to have long conversations about deep shit with because your perspective is so different to mine tbh. And to add: I get your point about how for example "freedom is good" isnt based on some sort of objective reality. But we have to also consider, that what makes us feel happy, or unhappy, doesnt come from semiotics. We had feelings of happiness, sadness, etc, before semiotics. Thats why I think we still can have moral ground rules, because they would be based on how humanity as a whole feels and what we need in order to function well.

The fact that morality is subjective doesn't have implications such that all rules are illegitimate. Just that the legitimacy of those rules aren't objective facts. We're capable of recognizing that morality is subjective while also holding ourselves and others to standards of behavior. In fact, we have to do that. It's not only inevitable, its necessary for any intermingling of personalities.

The principle that you mentioned is a good one, and it's worth holding people to. As it relates to the context of this thread, though, whatshisface didn't really violate it. 

I do appreciate your decorum in this exchange, though, and your diplomacy.

I agree with you and I think our moral codes should be based on how we can function and be a healthy, happy society. (such as offering good education and basic needs for people)  Maybe this doesnt and shouldnt include name-calling. Ive only noticed in my own life, and in the life of those close to me, that being a happy, healthy human does include things such as not bullying others and that reading comments insulting your looks can be really upsetting. I dont think calling someone ugly online, in the comment section is necessarily "bullying", but I dont think it can have any positive outcomes either. Thats why I think I felt the need to point out, that nobody would want that done to them or someone they care about. And yea, I think its good to have conversations with people who you dont agree with, thats how I form my opinions and these type of conversations keep modifying them so thank you for explaining your views as well

No they wouldnt magically go bad in a day but imagine if someone bought 5 of whatever meat they wanted (with adequate refrigeration and stuff) until their expiration date and 1 of them was bad before the date. I work at a grocery store: you'd be surprised how many people take expiry dates as the time the manufacturer guarantees, no matter what, they can eat it until. "Hi I bought this yogurt two weeks ago and the expiry date is in two weeks and I left this one on the counter for three hours and it grew mould there must be something wrong with it." Not so much of that, actually, because people understand that temperature can make refrigerated food go bad faster, but a big hitter is bread going bad before the expiry date and being brought back. Bud, it's probably been exposed to air with mould spores when you opened it or something that made it go bad faster than usual, the expiry date mostly just indicates how long they expect it to not grow mould sealed on the shelf. If you never opened it and it was mouldy before the expiry, that would be a bit different... but seriously? You opened it. And it's a recommendation of selling buy for grocers and using by for consumers, not any sort of promise it will be good until that point...

If you don't prepare it properly before consumption, you may end up with food poisoning, and you would get sick if it has been contaminated with bacteria.

To all the previous commenters: you act like we want the government and regulations to disappear. Not true. There should be a fine balance between a reasonable and unreasonable government. Not too much control and not too little. The people advocating for the government to receive any more power (on average) than it currently has are severely ignorant. If you want a new government regulation, better to take one away that is not wanted, etc.

Any and all regulations and government action is funded by taking money from the hard-working middle class because the lower class usually doesn't make enough to pay much in taxes and the upper class will always be able to afford the accountants and lawyers required to squeeze their money into loopholes in the tax system.

As such, you need to weigh every government activity against the idea that you are literally doing it on the back of the middle class. Sometimes this is fine - we need a military for defense, police for law and order, courts to maintain civil justice - while other times this is ridiculous - my local PD doesn't need a crowd control tank and there's no reason we should be taking control of land because an owl lives there.

There's an alternative - let people donate their would-be tax dollars to preservation societies, anti-poverty groups, and standardization bodies. If we all agree that we "need" these things and they benefit "everyone," then obviously people will pay for them, right?

This is such a bullshit millennial commercial that makes problems out of non existent issues. First...the sell by date is not the same as the use by date, hence the words "sell by" its for the store to make sure they're not selling product that goes bad right after its purchased. Depending on the food, that item should be good for days to even weeks by the sell by date. Second...yes milk is homogenized but that doesn't mean milk is safe to drink forever and ever. The reason milk spoils is because bacteria begins to form in the milk after a certain time. It's also not good to drink milk pass the date even if it smells good because there is still bacteria that has formed in the milk, it just hasn't caused it to spoil yet. To say that you can drink milk pass the sell by and never get sick is completely assanign. You think if you kept milk around for a year and drank it you would have no chance of getting sick? Come on. Plus; why on earth would you ever drink spoiled milk anyway? As far as the chips go with the best by a certain time is because chips have a long shelf life when kept hermetically sealed and that date is a mere suggestion to eat around that time so the manufacturer can garuntee its freshness. On the off chance you keep your chips a long time and they're a bit stail. The date even implies "best by" this date just as "use by" implies use up to this date only. Either the actors and creators of the video cannot decipher simple directions, or this is another another phantom issue concocted by millennials just to complain about government and authority. It's more of a gratitude thing. America is so greatly blessed with an abundance of food while THERE ARE MILLIONS of starving children and adults around the world going to bed hungry every night. Whereas in America we simply take all our easily accessible food for granted. To put it simply: "We're SPOILED brats!" Let the power grid be hit by a REAL cyberattack or a powerful blast from the sun and we'll all be looking in all the dumpsters for food for the first couple days of the outage and THEN - no food at all for anyone because there won't be no gas, no ATM's, no electricity, no phones and no trucks to deliver any food anywhere. This kind of major power grid outage won't last for only days or weeks but most likely it will go on for months. Believe me, someday IT WILL HAPPEN and then we'll realize what the suffering hungry around the world are presently experiencing. Also, trashed food ends up in the landflll where eventually it turns into methane - a climate warming green gas.

Mark Pfeifer How does that have anything to do with the initial question? He asked how not throwing away food would change the fact that there are millions starving. You failed to answer any of this and answered how we're spoiled by taking food for granted. As for the initial question, this could help because it would create an even greater abundance of food, which could feed those who are hungry. There are of course problems delivering the food, but with an abundance of food, that option is at least possible.

You nailed it in your last sentence. I think the issue is about food being wasted AT HOME. That's WHY I answered the way I did BECAUSE how do you really save and properly distribute the food you save at home? It's also been said that IF we could eliminate all this waste then there would actually be enough food to feed everyone in the world. What I feel is the much bigger problem in food waste is the huge amount of food that grocery stores continue to throw out, and this I've had real experience in dealing with the last four years as I have a food ministry for the homeless. I prepare 40 snack bags a week with a cold drink, a snack mix, yogurt, candy bar, etc, and I distribute these bags to homeless people outside a homeless shelter in Dallas. And guess what? I don't pay one dime for any of this food. It's food that I salvage from dumpsters near where I live. All this food is packaged and safe to eat as I know all about how to handle this food safely with refrigeration, etc. So, this is the food that could easily be saved and given to homeless shelters, churches or distributed directly to homeless souls as I do with most of what I salvage. Believe me, this grocery store waste is sickening. For example A couple years ago I actually found 3,000 full-size Baby Ruth candy bars expired by a mere two weeks in sealed cases alongside a dumpster on a loading dock of a grocery store. Had I not salvaged all these candy bars in the middle of the night they were destined for the landfill the following day. I gave 2,000 to a food pantry and the remaining 1,000 I distribured myself to homeless people near various shelters. Therefore, gorcery store waste is a major source of waste food that could be fed to hungry people in your own city.

These people will not be fed unless they can offer money, full stop.  Any food company would supply these countries if their products are purchased.  What you guys are discussing is charity, charity is only ever done by companies as a form of advertisment, meaning if more food was in supply, the amount of charity would not increase as a result, donations are a money game like anything else.  what most likely would happen if people didn't waste as much food is that the cost of food would go down in the local market due to a changed supply/demand ratio.  This lower cost may help poorer countries access the foods, but this would change the supply/demand ratio again bringing the price of food back out of reach, so really the price saving would be localized to existing markets.  In short, the starving people will still starve, the price of our food would go down.

Another answer: I think it should be rather obvious that NOT throwing away food from your kitchen is not IN ANY WAY going to rectify the hunger of anyone outside the members of your own family. Which IF you're on a limited budget then you better save this food as it's good money foolishly going out the door.

You're getting too complicated. WHY? Things are going to be changing BIG TIME real soon thanks to some forward thinkers in France. As of one year ago, a law was passed in France forbidding any grocery store in France from throwing out any so-called expired food. This food can no longer go in the dumpster unless it's really spoiled. Rather the stores are obligated by law to give this food to 501non-profits or to churches for distribution to needy people. If they don't they receive major fines and after three fines they will be going to jail.. And some states in this country have recently passed similar laws so in the not too distance future a lot of this foolish waste will be eliminated. And you're mistaken that companies only give food as advertisement. Many corporations give major food donations to big city food banks on a regular basis. Yes, it.s CHARITY!

I've seen grocery stores throwing out chocolate months from expiry because it has a Christmas label on it. 

Also, most shelters either have to or feel the need to throw out expired products donated to them because they're distributing it to other people.

Also, depending on where you are, there might be more local regulations that require stores to not sell expired product.

Also, the consumer has been trained so well that they wouldn't buy expired product even if it was sold for the most part.

Also, those that would ask for a discount. Often, the grocery store loses money on giving the discounts that people ask for on these products because the alternative, claiming them as a loss and bad product and throwing them out, often actually gets the store more of its money back. There's no monetary incentive to sell expired products.

In Australia there's laws regarding this.  

'Best Before' legally means that the food is expected to not taste its best after this date but that the food will remain safe to eat for a long period of time afterwards in which it's expected that the product would reasonably be assumed to have been eaten before this period runs out.

'Use By' legally means that the product is expected to not be safe to consume after this date.  There are many ways in which this can legally be determined.  The best method is controlled, scientific tests at recommended temperatures and storage to see when the contamination of the food with bacteria reaches what is considered unsafe levels.  Smaller manufactures just usually look at other similar products and then err on the side of caution so as to not get fined and/or sued for being wrong.  Funnily enough it's the larger manufactures which tend to have longer 'Use By' dates.  

And then there's things such as canned goods which don't need any labelling.

At least with the Use By dates there is actually a specific reason for those dates chosen. They are chosen based on predictability. Those are the dates where it's no longer easy to predict under reasonable assumptions that the food will still be safe to consume. They are also chosen based on chemical processes that occur within the food. Milk is a great example of this since it has a nice wide variety of chemical processes by which it transforms into other chemicals which we would not consider milk but may consider cheese curds or any number of things. It's not an exact date like Adam states. It's just an estimate.

As most of us know, proper storage can greatly extend those dates. The store I worked at in the past, which was a well known and respected franchise store would even answer any questions about storage customers may have. In small it was corporate crap to make people feel safe buying there but the bulk of it was us workers wanting to help educate anyone interested in good storage practice because those procedures really worked and were easily achievable with ordinary home appliances.
I am very thankful for uncovering the truth to me.

Most people, including Adam, are missing a very important point - litigation. Yes, many items are good beyond the expiration or best if used by dates. But the threat of litigation makes many companies put dates on food earlier than the actual date, which covers them in cases where idiots might leave the milk out for two days, then check the expiration date and see it's "still good." At least the expiration dates being sooner help protect companies against many (not all) idiots. Those dates protect the companies from getting sued and having to raise their prices even more to pay useless litigation.

Funny story: a long time ago my church youth group did a camp out behind the building (which was a school building before it was a church.) We had some breakfast the next morning including cereal and milk. We kept the leftover milk in the fridge in the middle school/ high school room. It eventually expired but we all decided we were going to keep it as an experiment to see how bad it could get. The sell by date is when food tastes best.
The use by date is when you have to eat or drink it.

In the UK we have a clear system.

Sell by dates are for the shop.
Best Before dates describe when the food tastes best/is best quality but is still safe to eat afterwards.
Use By dates are based on the average amount of time it takes the bacteria in the food to build to an unsafe level or for the food to turn, and is usually dated a little before the shortest time it goes off under normal storage conditions so it can be fine past the date but you want to be careful.

The only exception is with tinned foods or dry foods which don't spoil, as the UK government gives a maximum shelf life for any product. 

It's a pretty good system so we know when things will taste stale and when they are no longer safe.

Hey these video facts aren't true - here are the 2 real rules.

1. If the label says best before 25th November, it means it is still safe to eat after 25th November. Eg, crisps. 

2. If the label says use by 25th November, it becomes unsafe to eat it after 25th November. Eg, chicken. 

THESE ARE REAL

These rules only apply when the food is stored correctly

Side note - canned and dried foods are "best before" products which will still be safe to eat years later.

column13:
Well obviously, but everything is covered in bacteria. Even milk. This video is 100% correct, fully pasteurized milk doesn't contain any harmful bacteria. What you're smelling is the normal bacteria commonly found in milk (and completely healthy to drink) converting it into lactic acid, which makes it smell sour. Nothing is wrong with drinking "sour" or "spoiled' milk as long as there's no noticeable changes like mold.

Source: Work and live on a farm.

Canned food is also certainly NOT safe indefinitely. The coating on the inside of the cans will eventually break down after a few years, then it will diseminate through the food making it rather unpleasant. Then the can will corrode, further spoiling the food. That will eventually cause air to get in and at that point it's done for.

We've basically got the same problem here in the UK where we have "best before", "display until" and "use by" dates. IIRC, the only one that stores have to pay attention to are the "use by" and "display until" dates, but then it's up to the company as to how to treat the "best before" date. One shop I worked in wouldn't sell anything past any date at all, while another could sell certain items for up to a month past the "best before" date.

Best bit is, we're almost all taught what those dates actually mean, and that they're largely arbitrary, but we still have to just throw out stock anyway and it's so stupid. We know the system sucks, and when customers ask about it we're allowed to be completely honest about that fact (I've been known to step in and say "it's reduced to half-price because of the date on it, but it should be all right for another week or two if you store it properly" on multiple occasions). It seems to help a bit, but we're still throwing out food that's perfectly fine except for the date on it.

Oh, and eggs are ridiculous. Most of them have a "display until" and a "use by" date. We have to throw them out ON the "display until" date, despite the "use by" date still being a week or two away.

I remember reading that medicinal products are also often mislabeled. This statement was based on a research made on military stock: they checked drugs that are allegedly expired for their potency because the turnover on military stock is huge, it's a great expense, they thought they might reduce waste of resources. They found, producers overshoot with these dates, and somene medicine was just as good months after it's expired date. Other drugs, like antibiotics just lose their potency slowly, so that if you, for example, live in dire times when no new drugs available (eg., war), you just take an increased dose depending on how expired the drug is, and you are good.

Bacteria in Milk

Most types of bacteria are killed by heat when milk is pasteurized. It‚Äôs possible for milk to become contaminated after it‚Äôs pasteurized, but even under clean conditions, some sneaky bacterial spores survive processing. Not only that, but they also grow under cold temperatures, so refrigeration slows them down but doesn‚Äôt stop them. These thermoduric bacteria are the ones usually responsible for milk spoilage beyond the expiration date on the carton. Several different types of thermoduric bacteria exist. The extent of the spoilage depends on the specific bacteria

Food Poisoning

If you drink milk past the expiration date, you run the risk of developing food poisoning from unhealthy bacteria that might have grown in the milk. Food poisoning can be so mild you might not even realize you have it, but it can be severe in some cases. You might develop stomach cramps, nausea, diarrhea or a fever. It can last for hours or days, and you might start to feel the effects of the bad milk within a couple hours of drinking it. Since raw milk isn‚Äôt pasteurized, it has a better chance of containing bacteria and can cause serious illness, especially for anyone with a compromised immune system.

most of these old laws, if they still exist, are not enforceable. This includes the 'mince pie on Christmas ban', 'the Vicar must train the men of the village in archery every Sunday', and even all those 'shooting a Welshman with a crossbow in the bounds of York' laws. Not even every law that is legally enforcable is enforced.

Onto my favourite British law, the legal drinking age. There's a variety and there's a decent argument for it causing a better drinking culture, but at least in England a newborn baby can be given alcohol if prescribed by a doctor. the legal age for supervised drink on a private premise is five with your parent's permission, this is generally used to allow kids to join in the New Year cheers in my experience with a single glass. You can legally order some forms of alcohol with a meal once you reach 16 (I personally did at that age), and from 18 onwards you can buy and drink whatever you want. There's actual logic in a slow introduction to alcohol, most people I know who had one went off to university and rarely drunk.
